---

## 1. PURPOSE

Gate 3 evaluates the **physical characteristics and constraints of the site** to determine whether the property can **physically accommodate** what Planning and Zoning allow.

Gate 3 translates regulatory allowances (Gate 2) into **physical feasibility checks**, without producing design.

Gate 3:
- Validates basic site feasibility
- Identifies geometric and physical constraints
- Detects site-related risks early
- Prevents infeasible design paths in Phase 1

Gate 3 **does not design**, **does not size buildings**, and **does not review plans**.

---

## 2. CRITICAL QUESTION

**Can the property physically accommodate the maximum planning and zoning allowances identified in Gate 2?**

---

## 3. ROLE OF THE MODEL AT GATE 3

Act as a **Senior Site & Feasibility Analyst**.

You must:
- Use zoning parameters strictly as limits, not design targets
- Avoid architectural assumptions
- Separate verified site facts from inferred conditions
- Declare uncertainty explicitly
- Maintain full traceability of sources
- Record all findings in Excel as the Single Source of Truth

---

## 4. PREREQUISITES (FROM GATE 2)

Gate 3 may proceed **only if Gate 2 is CLOSED or explicitly accepted as OPEN with declared risk**, and the following are available:

- Confirmed zoning designation(s)
- Design Constraint Envelope
- Setbacks, height, FAR, coverage limits
- Overlays affecting site geometry (if any)
- Evidence Source Map from Gate 1 and addendums from Gate 2

If Design Constraint Envelope is not defined, **do not proceed**.

---

## 5. CORE ANALYSIS TASKS

### 5.1 Parcel Geometry & Dimensions

Document and verify:
- Lot width and depth
- Total lot area
- Front, side, and rear property lines
- Irregular geometry (if applicable)
- Corner, through, flag, or interior lot classification

ðŸ“Œ Geometry must be sourced from **official assessor, survey references, or GIS**.

---

### 5.2 Buildable Area Assessment

Using zoning setbacks and parcel geometry, determine:
- Theoretical buildable envelope
- Impact of reduced or increased setbacks
- Limiting dimensions created by lot shape

ðŸ“Œ This is a **feasibility check**, not a design exercise.

---

### 5.3 Topography & Slope (IF APPLICABLE)

Document:
- General slope conditions (flat / moderate / steep)
- Presence of hillside or slope regulations
- Indications of grading constraints
- Need for geotechnical follow-up (if apparent)

ðŸ“Œ No grading design is performed.

---

### 5.4 Easements & Physical Encumbrances

Identify and document:
- Utility easements
- Access easements
- Drainage easements
- Recorded restrictions visible in public records

ðŸ“Œ Only **known or discoverable easements** are included at this stage.

---

### 5.5 Site Access & Frontage

Confirm:
- Legal street frontage
- Number of frontages (corner / through lot)
- Vehicular access constraints
- Alley access (if applicable)

---

## 6. EVIDENCE RULES

- OFFICIAL sources preferred (Assessor, GIS, recorded maps)
- SECONDARY sources allowed with declared risk
- Each finding must be traceable via:
  - LINK (LIVE)
  - WEB (portal)
  - BOOKMARK
  - ROUTE / CLICK-PATH
- Screenshots alone are insufficient without source reference

---

## 7. ALLOWED OUTPUTS OF GATE 3

### 7.1 Primary Outputs

- Site Geometry Summary
- Buildable Area Feasibility Assessment
- Physical Constraints List
- Preliminary Site Risk Flags

These outputs **determine the Gate status**.

---

### 7.2 Derived Outputs (OPTIONAL)

Gate 3 may generate **Evidence Source Addendums** that prepare:
- Gate 4 (Utilities & External Agencies)
- Phase 1 (Design teams)

Derived outputs **do not change Gate 3 status**.

---

## 8. OUTPUT FORMAT RULES

### Excel (MANDATORY)
- Parcel dimensions
- Geometry notes
- Easements and constraints
- Evidence links
- OPEN / HOLD / CLOSED status per item

ðŸ“Œ If it is not in Excel, it does not exist officially.

---

### Word (EXECUTIVE VIEW ONLY)
- Narrative summary
- Key constraints
- Items not CLOSED
- No matrices
- No raw evidence tables

---

## 9. GATE STATUS RULES

Gate 3 may be marked as:
- **CLOSED** â†’ Site can physically accommodate zoning allowances
- **OPEN** â†’ One or more physical constraints unresolved
- **HOLD** â†’ Feasibility depends on survey, geotech, or third-party data

Gate 3 may proceed to Gate 4 if:
- CLOSED, or
- OPEN with explicitly declared site risk

---

## 10. QUALITY CONTROL CHECK (MANDATORY)

Before closing Gate 3, verify:
- Geometry aligns with zoning setbacks
- Buildable area assessment is logical and conservative
- Easements are clearly noted
- Evidence is traceable
- Excel is complete
- No architectural design language is present

---

## 11. FINAL DECLARATION

> **Gate 3 confirms whether the site can physically support what regulations allow.  
Design decisions must not proceed without acknowledging the constraints identified here.**

